I am studying geometric measure theory ( Herbert Federer - Geometric measure theory ) and I have a question about class $r$ homotopies. Here's the definition, from p. 363, Section 4.1.9: Suppose $U$ is an open subset of $\mathbb{R}^{n}$ , $V$ is an open subset of $\mathbb{R}^{v}$ $f$ , and $g$ are functions mapping $U$ into $V$ . A homotopy of class $r$ from $f$ to $g$ is a map $$ h: A 	imes U ightarrow V $$ of class $r$ such that $A$ is an open subinterval of $\mathbb{R}$ , $0 \in A$ , $1 \in A$ , $$ h(0, x)=f(x) 	ext { and } h(1, x)=g(x) 	ext { for } x \in U. $$ Whenever $t \in A$ we define $$ h_{t}: U ightarrow V, \quad h_{t}(x)=h(t, x) 	ext { for } x \in U, $$ hence $h_{0}=f$ and $h_{1}=g$ ; in case $r \geq 1$ we also define $$ h_{t}: U ightarrow \mathbb{R}^{v}, \quad h_{t}(x)=\langle(1,0), D h(t, x)angle 	ext { for } x \in U, $$ hence $\langle(v, w), D h(t, x)angle=v h_{t}(x)+\left\langle w, D h_{t}(x)ightangle$ for $t \in A$ , $x \in U$ , $v \in \mathbb{R}$ , $w \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ . Now my question is about the last 3 lines: in case $r \geq 1$ we also define $$ h_{t}: U ightarrow \mathbb{R}^{v}, \quad h_{t}(x)=\langle(1,0), D h(t, x)angle 	ext { for } x \in U, $$ hence $\langle(v, w), D h(t, x)angle=v h_{t}(x)+\left\langle w, D h_{t}(x)ightangle$ for $t \in A, x \in U, v \in \mathbb{R}, w \in \mathbb{R}^{n}$ . Actually, we know that $\langle v, Df(a)angle = v \cdot 
abla f(a)$ . Also, in the last line it is mentioned that $w \in \mathbb{R}^n$ , hence $0 = (0, \dotsc,0) \in \mathbb{R}^n$ . Now, we have: $$h_t(x)= \langle (1, 0, \dotsc, 0), Dh(t,x) angle$$ which is equal to  egin{align} h_t(x) &= (1, 0, \dotsc, 0) \cdot 
abla h(t,x)\ &= (1, 0 , \dotsc, 0) \cdot \left( rac{\partial h}{\partial t},  rac{\partial h}{\partial x_1}, \dotsc,  rac{\partial h}{\partial x_n}ight) \ &=  rac{\partial h}{\partial t}.\end{align} Now, my question is that why it is said that $h_t: U ightarrow \mathbb{R}^{
u}$ ? I mean, now we should see that $ rac{\partial h}{\partial t} \in \mathbb{R}^{
